RT @koolwhp: I was not expecting the first 3/4 of The King's Man to be fairly affecting anti-war movie about World War I

Anyways, I still have hot angry tears when I think about the "That was so badass!", "Man, we're just a generation of pussies, aren't we?", "Those were real men" comments I heard from movie-goers when the lights came up after I watched Dunkirk in 2017. Horrifying. We need bumpers.

A fucking comic book action movie masterfully ensured what even a fancy heavy-hitting film like Dunkirk was too pridefully artsy to do 👀

TKM had no precedent, no need, no incentive to go as hard as it did 🥺 it made no sense to take that on and I'm here for it

Common Trope: "Character Motivated (and Consequently Doomed) by Earnest Naïveté" Experiences a Serious Reckoning/Change of Heart that Undooms Him or Positively Changes His Outcome.

TKM said NO, we will NOT give you even that opportunity to romanticize the horrors of war.

Even Conrad's eventual realization, that there is nothing in war - no act of bravery, no display of brotherhood, no virtuous suffering - that builds better men and warrants its cost, is not enough to save him. Which, like, is pretty fucking rare in these types of stories.

Okay final take: I appreciate that when TKM bowled audiences down the alley of "war is bad, actually", they made sure to put the fucking bumpers on the lane so that there's no way any reasonable viewer could find enough ambiguity in the narrative for a different takeaway.

I'll add that I also think our collective familiarity with WWI - its players, politics, events - is so fucking poor. And TKM doesn't account for that, which leaves a lot of heavy-lifting (re: historical context) to an audience that isn't equipped or willing to do it.

But I have never in my life seen such an unexpected unequivocal commitment to such an unexpected ideology from such an unexpected genre. I've always loved things that don't go together - "creative tension" or whatever. And it's undeniable in The King's Man and I love it for that.

Is The King's Man art? No. Is it without fault? No. Do I think Oswald Oxford and his organization are, as the story claims, "pacifist"? Absolutely not. Do I agree with the arc of Oxford's "pacifism" and acceptance of conflicting truths? Also no. Was some of TKM dumb? Definitely.

And I also imagine the still-pretty-radical sentiment that "yes, war is irredeemably bad" is jarringly unfamiliar and uncomfortable to audiences, particularly in the unexpected context of a super spy comic book action movie.

Which is exactly why I loved The King's Man.

There is no nobility, no honor, no valor, no virtue, no glory to be found in war. No man is made better by war.

I imagine a large chunk of the audience is put off by the infusion of a deeply emotional narrative alongside the series' beloved and absurd action sequences.

I have never seen anything like it. And I think the unexpectedness of the story is why people hate it. It deviates markedly from the original movie's camp and absurdity. And it offers, with no subtlety, a very political, deeply spiritual, unpopular and counter-cultural ideology:

I can understand why people hated it: an action-comedy spy movie franchise adapted from a comic book series reveals its titular organization's emotional origin story as one bourne from anti-war morality and the horrors of WWI.
Maybe one of my hottest takes ever: I loved The King's Man.

I hate that man. He's despicable. I kinda hope he burns in Hell - a strong statement for me because I don't think I believe in the construct. But lemme tell y'all: those men in that AutoZone made me just as angry and made me feel just as alone. Maybe that's displaced rage 12/?

Because...it is business as usual.

I'd gotten disconnected from my friend at that point but called my roommates to walk to the shop because I was too scared to finish walking home alone, in broad daylight, for fear he'd be waiting for me or see which house was mine. 11/?

Every man in that store saw me and heard me share what happened. Not a single one asked if I was okay. Or if I needed to use a phone. Or if I wanted them to call police. Or if they could check outside for the Silver SUV. They turned around and went back to business as usual. 10/?

I was sobbing and scared.
"Good afternoon, what are you looking for today?" - AutoZone employee
"I'm sorry, a man just followed me and tried to pull me into his car, I ran here to get away from him" - me, a visible wreck
"Oh. Okay. Next customer?" - AutoZone man
9/?

...and I didn't realize I was also crying until I burst into the AutoZone and hid against the wall while peering out the glass door to make sure he left and didn't follow or wait for me. Everyone in the store - employees, customers...all men - looked at me. 8/?

... shouting something and reached out towards my body. I froze, I felt trapped by his car and my fear, until my brain turned on and I shouted and turned to run back down the street to the nearest open building which was an AutoZone. I ran so fucking fast, screaming, 7/?

...when I felt weird and looked back over my shoulder again. The Silver SUV was right behind me. He saw me see him. He sped up alongside me and swerved his car in front of me, effectively cutting me off so I couldn't get past. He opened his passenger door, leaned across 6/?

...just in case Silver SUV was watching. I didn't want him to easily see where I lived. I have to do this all the time. I looked back when I turned onto the side street, didn't see the SUV and let my phone buddy know I was okay. I got about a third of the way down the street 5/?

The light turned and I hauled ass across the intersection, panting my location into the phone while my friend told me to let me know when I'd made it off the main drag and down the side street I lived off of. I consciously didn't take my normal direct side street 4/?

My phone buddy lived across the country but I wanted someone on the phone with me "just in case". I have to make these calls all the time. The crosswalk light hadn't turned yet and Silver SUV made a FOURTH pass, this time slow enough I could see the driver ogling 3/?

Waiting for the crosswalk light to change, this silver SUV rolled slowly past me. Not noteworthy - until I watched it roll by a second time. "Maybe they're lost, missed their turn", I remember thinking. On the third pass, my Hell No Sensor went off and I called a friend 2/?

Today I'm thinking about the day last year when I was walking home from the bus stop and I realized a man was following me in his car. It was a bright, sunny September afternoon and I was wearing a skirt to my knees, a sweatshirt, and sneakers. 1/?

Because it IS common. And it's only a piece of this person's story! And not making a larger deal out of someone's history of substance use serves to bypass the stigma. I have a mixed bag of feelings about the Bachelor franchise but this part felt pretty cool and subtly important.

Initially I was disappointed the show didn't take the opportunity to educate viewers on something incredibly common and incredibly stigmatized. But when I thought about it (while watching more episodes 🥴), the casual and momentary introduction of this story is exactly the move.

AND after the contestant Zac, who works as an "addiction specialist", disclosed his past struggles with usage, the show just...moved on. It wasn't portrayed as a concerning red flag, there wasn't any exploitative prying...it was just a piece of him and not his whole identity.

Okay bear with me: I don't think starring on the Bachelorette is a meaningful aspirational achievement AND there's something really wonderful and important about a contestant disclosing a past substance use disorder and still being shown with a loving family and successful life.

Everyone is gonna be vaccinated before the family that lives in their car. I'm a realist - teachers, with stable jobs and reliable health insurance, are gonna get their shots before poor folks - but it'll be because this country hates poor folks, not because they value teachers.

Truthfully, I think calls to prioritize teachers are coming from an upper middle class economic standpoint and not a genuine concern for human welfare, for the least of these. And you know the white burbs are gonna see those vaccines before urban and rural low-income schools.

You're welcome to disagree - that's why it's a hot take 😬 I'm sorry if this hurts your feelings. It does not mean I think less of educators. We intrinsically want to give everything we can to teachers - but this would be at the expense of folks in far more dire situations.
RT @_chismosa_: Rich people did not experience the same pandemic as working class people and now they get the vaccine first. It’s actually…

I say this as a fierce advocate for education and someone who knows schools/teaching are not just about education anymore. My hot take pains me. But people who *can* work from home, whose income is reliable, even if meager, cannot be prioritized while there is vaccine scarcity.

People who work in direct social service, who are going to see an influx of folks in need of shelter after rent moratoriums expire, should be prioritized over educators. Grocery store workers ahead of teachers. Hell, I think most hospitality workers should come before teachers.

Working from home sucks, schooling from home sucks, we get it. We know. But the essentiality, on a survival level, is not there. It really is not. After HCWs, public transit workers are more essential than teachers. The elderly, immunocompromised, and BIPOC should be prioritized.

Hot take: I've seen a bit of online yadda-yadda saying we need to prioritize teachers in vaccine deployment. I disagree. Teachers are undervalued and underpaid but they are *not* essential the way healthcare and sanitation workers are. That sounds shitty but it's true.

AND there are SO MANY BULLSHIT METRICS beyond age and gender (and I am only experienced with the binary!) that we calculate into worth/desirability. I'm feeling defeatist which is uncool but the individual work is fucking hard when it feels like there is little societal shift.

@MacitheMermaid Wildly overpriced non-necessity that is not just functionally UNimpressive but also a very fickle delicate machine that tends to become a paperweight when something breaks.

That being said, I have a Mac right now BUT I bought it responsibly-used two years ago for $600.

AND YET I also don't think it's untrue. The way we measure each other and ourselves is truly bonkers and it's absolutely maddening to see and feel so starkly at a far earlier point in my life than people seem to talk about.

No man is ever gonna have to worry that if a six month or six year relationship doesn't work out, they'll have dramatically curtailed options, that a swath of women won't consider a man the same age desirable because we've decided he's now stale. It sounds insane BECAUSE IT IS.

Morality of the entire system aside, the infuriating part is that men are not measured by the same metrics we are. This isn't novel or unique to age/desirability. But goddamn if it doesn't make me wanna self-immolate that no ex of mine will ever be limited by this factor.

The valuation of women's youth is so depravedly acute that we also incur precipitous devaluation at any sign of aging, whether that's gray hair or simply the divulgence of a birth year. Despite knowing I can't possibly be assessed like a commodity, it doesn't change that I am.

The unfairness of that reality is... debilitating. And sure, gimme a "Not All..." what-have-you but I am speaking both broadly and to my experience, not about your specific stellar partner you met in school where you're set up to engage with similarly-aged peers. Keep it 🙅‍♀️🙊

Like, that's actually insane?? I'm still objectively young in the second half of my 20s and I'm also still very objectively hot - both are gross metrics of desirability but I should pass muster. AND YET I am already considered "too old" and therefore undesirable BY MEN MY OWN AGE

My momma's experience is not different from what I've heard from other women who've aged before me. And I don't actually give a shit about a bullshit celebrity piece only finding appeal in men's aging. But it's infuriating little has changed and that I'm feeling this IN MY 20s!!!

I place incredible value on the spiritual element of this endeavor, unlearning youth as a woman's beauty and that her worth (and opportunity) is derived from desirability. But HOLY SHIT it's demoralizing to constantly be checked, to viscerally experience the opposite so often.

AND YET what does that work really matter *in this world*? It's hard to know. It's a trial to not give in, especially while I can still squeeze a modicum of fake benefit out of this perverse reality. Why work so hard to subvert it when we're still gonna be subjected to it?

You can rail against the misogyny and cruelty of our world's objectifying valuation of female youth. You can do the work of unlearning this fuckery and avoid internalizing this metric. You can be beautiful or ugly or in between, knowing it means nothing about you (or anyone else)

My momma is a tough old bird. She was a tough young bird too. It breaks me that someone who is so beautiful and who also *never* found her worth in her physicality (a feat to resist this narrative) still inevitably succumbs to this deep-rooted, pervasive, ugly societal cancer.

Of course my mother is still beautiful. She's also 70. Without youth and it's corresponding appeal, people see through her, past her, see no one at all. She can't get help at stores, doctors don't listen to concerns, people move about her in public as if she isn't there. AND YET

I remember my mother, who spent an above-average amount of her life being traditionally (and effortlessly 🥺) beautiful, rage-crying about the invisibility of aging as a woman. She wasn't upset about not being young or "pretty" anymore but because people literally don't see her.

I'm still very much in my twenties (🤞) so there will come a day and a year where I stop seeing gains in the sad normative type of attractive. It'll be sooner than I'm ready for and I'll be upset but I'll also know that's not where my worth lies (reminder to self 👀🥴🥺). AND YET

For the record, I have literally only gotten hotter with age thus far. Like, every day, every year, I am markedly more beautiful than the one that came before. Like the sad normative type of attractive - though it's also true of the wonderful internal spiritual type too. AND YET

This is acutely pissing me off at this point in my life for so many reasons. Not even touching the generally problematic fixation with beauty and aging. Just raging about the dramatically different framing between men and women in regards to aging, gray hair, wrinkles, maturity.
